article.headline: Kirilenko, Harpring bring double-double punch
article.linkText: Jazz take 11th of last 12 meetings vs. Bulls
article.story:
CHICAGO (AP) -- The Utah Jazz are going to take a well-deserved break. Andrei Kirilenko had 26 points and a career-high 16 rebounds Monday night, and the Jazz beat the Chicago Bulls 92-80 to end their six-games-in-nine-nights road trip with an even record. "Since we have three days off, we can spend all our energy," Kirilenko said. "I think all the guys spent everything. Yesterday we had a pretty tough game against Detroit, and they beat us easily. So we tried to come back today with a little deeper attitude." The Jazz still had problems with turnovers, giving the ball up 26 times. But they outrebounded the Bulls 49-34, took advantage of Chicago's sloppy first half and made their free throws when they counted. The Bulls did their best to make it interesting, though. Trailing by 20 early in the third quarter, they went on a furious rally and cut Utah's lead to 79-72 on a fast break dunk by Corie Blount with 3:46 to play. But they couldn't get any closer, and were forced to foul the Jazz down the stretch. "It wasn't a pretty game. It was a sloppy one," said Matt Harpring, who had 15 points and 14 rebounds. "But a win is a win." The Bulls finished with six players in double figures, but they couldn't overcome their slow start. They were 27-of-37 from the line, including seven misses in the last five minutes of the first half. Chicago also gave up 22 points on 15 turnovers as it lost for the seventh time in the last nine games. Kendall Gill led the Bulls with 13 points. "It's not even about wins and losses right now," coach Scott Skiles said. "It's about the level of effort and doing things the right way. We're searching right now for a unit that can do that on a consistent basis." Things went sour for the Bulls early, with Skiles calling a timeout 66 seconds into the game because of sloppy play. He yanked Jamal Crawford a minute later, and didn't put him in the rest of the half. "I told guys my patience was wearing just a little bit thin on the lack of execution and knowing our handful of simple plays," Skiles said. "We blew a couple early and I called a timeout. We did not execute again, and I started taking guys out." But it took a while for the message to click. After the Jazz fell behind 8-4, they made nine of their next 10 shots as part of a 21-4 run. They wound up outscoring Chicago 27-14 in the first half, and shooting 61 percent. Kendall Gill made a 22-footer with 7:57 left in the half to cut Utah's lead to 35-28, its smallest since late in the first quarter. But Chicago didn't make a field goal the rest of the half, and Utah closed with a 17-7 run to take a 52-35 lead. "He was pretty animated," Crawford said of Skiles' halftime speech. "He was upset and he had reason to be. They're a good team, but it's their sixth game in nine nights. There's no reason we shouldn't have won that game." The Jazz did slow down in the second half. Kirilenko's 3-pointer with 8:49 left in the third gave Utah a 59-39 lead, its largest of the night. But Rick Brunson made a pair of free throws with two minutes left in the third to start an 8-2 run that cut Utah's lead to 71-58 going into the fourth. Kirk Hinrich's little running jumper with 7:37 left got the Bulls within double digits, 73-64. And after a Kirilenko tip-in, Hinrich drilled a huge 3, pulling Chicago to 75-67. The Bulls got within seven twice, but wouldn't get any closer.

Game notes
Utah has beaten the Bulls in 11 of their last 12 games. ... Kendall Gill led the Bulls with 13 points. ... Skiles wore No. 4 as a player, in part, because he admired Sloan so much. "I liked the way he played, and he coaches in a manner similar to the way he played," Skiles said. "He has his principles, and he insists upon them and they try to get people who do things the right way. I think he's been underestimated for a long time." Asked if he was aware how much Skiles respected him, Sloan smiled. "Usually, if anybody has anything to say about me, it's the opposite," he said. "Because I didn't leave a very good taste in people's mouths when I played. I wasn't a very nice guy." ... Johnny "Red" Kerr, the Bulls first coach and now the team's TV analyst, had knee surgery Monday.
